comment:
* Representation of the capabilities of an active network. Instances are * typically obtained through * {@link NetworkCallback#onCapabilitiesChanged(Network, NetworkCapabilities)} * or {@link ConnectivityManager#getNetworkCapabilities(Network)}. *

* This replaces the old {@link ConnectivityManager#TYPE_MOBILE} method of * network selection. Rather than indicate a need for Wi-Fi because an * application needs high bandwidth and risk obsolescence when a new, fast * network appears (like LTE), the application should specify it needs high * bandwidth. Similarly if an application needs an unmetered network for a bulk * transfer it can specify that rather than assuming all cellular based * connections are metered and all Wi-Fi based connections are not.

variables.name: mPrivateDnsBroken
variables.comment: Set to true when private DNS is broken.

variables.name: mRequestorUid
variables.comment: * Uid of the app making the request.

variables.name: mRequestorPackageName
variables.comment: * Package name of the app making the request.

variables.name: mNetworkCapabilities
variables.comment:
* Represents the network's capabilities.  If any are specified they will be satisfied
     * by any Network that matches all of them.

variables.name: mUnwantedNetworkCapabilities
variables.comment: * If any capabilities specified here they must not exist in the matching Network.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_MMS
variables.comment:
* Indicates this is a network that has the ability to reach the
     * carrier's MMSC for sending and receiving MMS messages.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_SUPL
variables.comment:
* Indicates this is a network that has the ability to reach the carrier's
     * SUPL server, used to retrieve GPS information.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_DUN
variables.comment:
* Indicates this is a network that has the ability to reach the carrier's
     * DUN or tethering gateway.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_FOTA
variables.comment:
* Indicates this is a network that has the ability to reach the carrier's
     * FOTA portal, used for over the air updates.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_IMS
variables.comment:
* Indicates this is a network that has the ability to reach the carrier's
     * IMS servers, used for network registration and signaling.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_CBS
variables.comment:
* Indicates this is a network that has the ability to reach the carrier's
     * CBS servers, used for carrier specific services.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_WIFI_P2P
variables.comment:
* Indicates this is a network that has the ability to reach a Wi-Fi direct
     * peer.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_IA
variables.comment:
* Indicates this is a network that has the ability to reach a carrier's
     * Initial Attach servers.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_RCS
variables.comment:
* Indicates this is a network that has the ability to reach a carrier's
     * RCS servers, used for Rich Communication Services.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_XCAP
variables.comment:
* Indicates this is a network that has the ability to reach a carrier's
     * XCAP servers, used for configuration and control.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_EIMS
variables.comment:
* Indicates this is a network that has the ability to reach a carrier's
     * Emergency IMS servers or other services, used for network signaling
     * during emergency calls.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_NOT_METERED
variables.comment: * Indicates that this network is unmetered.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_INTERNET
variables.comment: * Indicates that this network should be able to reach the internet.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_NOT_RESTRICTED
variables.comment:
* Indicates that this network is available for general use.  If this is not set
     * applications should not attempt to communicate on this network.  Note that this
     * is simply informative and not enforcement - enforcement is handled via other means.
     * Set by default.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_TRUSTED
variables.comment:
* Indicates that the user has indicated implicit trust of this network.  This
     * generally means it's a sim-selected carrier, a plugged in ethernet, a paired
     * BT device or a wifi the user asked to connect to.  Untrusted networks
     * are probably limited to unknown wifi AP.  Set by default.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_NOT_VPN
variables.comment:
* Indicates that this network is not a VPN.  This capability is set by default and should be
     * explicitly cleared for VPN networks.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_VALIDATED
variables.comment:
* Indicates that connectivity on this network was successfully validated. For example, for a
     * network with NET_CAPABILITY_INTERNET, it means that Internet connectivity was successfully
     * detected.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_CAPTIVE_PORTAL
variables.comment:
* Indicates that this network was found to have a captive portal in place last time it was
     * probed.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_NOT_ROAMING
variables.comment: * Indicates that this network is not roaming.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_FOREGROUND
variables.comment:
* Indicates that this network is available for use by apps, and not a network that is being
     * kept up in the background to facilitate fast network switching.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_NOT_CONGESTED
variables.comment:
* Indicates that this network is not congested. *

* When a network is congested, applications should defer network traffic * that can be done at a later time, such as uploading analytics.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_NOT_SUSPENDED
variables.comment:
* Indicates that this network is not currently suspended. *

* When a network is suspended, the network's IP addresses and any connections * established on the network remain valid, but the network is temporarily unable * to transfer data. This can happen, for example, if a cellular network experiences * a temporary loss of signal, such as when driving through a tunnel, etc. * A network with this capability is not suspended, so is expected to be able to * transfer data.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_OEM_PAID
variables.comment:
* Indicates that traffic that goes through this network is paid by oem. For example,
     * this network can be used by system apps to upload telemetry data.
     * @hide

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_MCX
variables.comment:
* Indicates this is a network that has the ability to reach a carrier's Mission Critical
     * servers.

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_PARTIAL_CONNECTIVITY
variables.comment:
* Indicates that this network was tested to only provide partial connectivity.
     * @hide

variables.name: NET_CAPABILITY_TEMPORARILY_NOT_METERED
variables.comment:
* This capability will be set for networks that are generally metered, but are currently
     * unmetered, e.g., because the user is in a particular area. This capability can be changed at
     * any time. When it is removed, applications are responsible for stopping any data transfer
     * that should not occur on a metered network.

variables.name: MUTABLE_CAPABILITIES
variables.comment:
* Network capabilities that are expected to be mutable, i.e., can change while a particular
     * network is connected.

variables.name: NON_REQUESTABLE_CAPABILITIES
variables.comment:
* Network capabilities that are not allowed in NetworkRequests. This exists because the
     * NetworkFactory / NetworkAgent model does not deal well with the situation where a
     * capability's presence cannot be known in advance. If such a capability is requested, then we
     * can get into a cycle where the NetworkFactory endlessly churns out NetworkAgents that then
     * get immediately torn down because they do not have the requested capability.

variables.name: DEFAULT_CAPABILITIES
variables.comment: * Capabilities that are set by default when the object is constructed.

variables.name: RESTRICTED_CAPABILITIES
variables.comment:
* Capabilities that suggest that a network is restricted.
     * {@see #maybeMarkCapabilitiesRestricted}, {@see #FORCE_RESTRICTED_CAPABILITIES}

variables.name: FORCE_RESTRICTED_CAPABILITIES
variables.comment:
* Capabilities that force network to be restricted.
     * {@see #maybeMarkCapabilitiesRestricted}.

variables.name: UNRESTRICTED_CAPABILITIES
variables.comment:
* Capabilities that suggest that a network is unrestricted.
     * {@see #maybeMarkCapabilitiesRestricted}.

variables.name: CONNECTIVITY_MANAGED_CAPABILITIES
variables.comment: * Capabilities that are managed by ConnectivityService.

variables.name: TEST_NETWORKS_ALLOWED_CAPABILITIES
variables.comment:
* Capabilities that are allowed for test networks. This list must be set so that it is safe
     * for an unprivileged user to create a network with these capabilities via shell. As such,
     * it must never contain capabilities that are generally useful to the system, such as
     * INTERNET, IMS, SUPL, etc.

variables.name: mTransportTypes
variables.comment:
* Representing the transport type.  Apps should generally not care about transport.  A
     * request for a fast internet connection could be satisfied by a number of different
     * transports.  If any are specified here it will be satisfied a Network that matches
     * any of them.  If a caller doesn't care about the transport it should not specify any.

variables.name: TRANSPORT_CELLULAR
variables.comment: * Indicates this network uses a Cellular transport.

variables.name: TRANSPORT_WIFI
variables.comment: * Indicates this network uses a Wi-Fi transport.

variables.name: TRANSPORT_BLUETOOTH
variables.comment: * Indicates this network uses a Bluetooth transport.

variables.name: TRANSPORT_ETHERNET
variables.comment: * Indicates this network uses an Ethernet transport.

variables.name: TRANSPORT_VPN
variables.comment: * Indicates this network uses a VPN transport.

variables.name: TRANSPORT_WIFI_AWARE
variables.comment: * Indicates this network uses a Wi-Fi Aware transport.

variables.name: TRANSPORT_LOWPAN
variables.comment: * Indicates this network uses a LoWPAN transport.

variables.name: TRANSPORT_TEST
variables.comment:
* Indicates this network uses a Test-only virtual interface as a transport.
     *
     * @hide

variables.name: MIN_TRANSPORT
variables.comment: @hide

variables.name: MAX_TRANSPORT
variables.comment: @hide

variables.name: TEST_NETWORKS_ALLOWED_TRANSPORTS
variables.comment: * Allowed transports on a test network, in addition to TRANSPORT_TEST.

variables.name: mOwnerUid
variables.comment:
* UID of the app that owns this network, or Process#INVALID_UID if none/unknown. * *

This field keeps track of the UID of the app that created this network and is in charge of * its lifecycle. This could be the UID of apps such as the Wifi network suggestor, the running * VPN, or Carrier Service app managing a cellular data connection. * *

For NetworkCapability instances being sent from ConnectivityService, this value MUST be * reset to Process.INVALID_UID unless all the following conditions are met: * *

The caller is the network owner, AND one of the following sets of requirements is met: * *

    *
  1. The described Network is a VPN *
* *

OR: * *

    *
  1. The calling app is the network owner *
  2. The calling app has the ACCESS_FINE_LOCATION permission granted *
  3. The user's location toggle is on *
* * This is because the owner UID is location-sensitive. The apps that request a network could * know where the device is if they can tell for sure the system has connected to the network * they requested. * *

This is populated by the network agents and for the NetworkCapabilities instance sent by * an app to the System Server, the value MUST be reset to Process.INVALID_UID by the system * server.

variables.name: mAdministratorUids
variables.comment:
* UIDs of packages that are administrators of this network, or empty if none. * *

This field tracks the UIDs of packages that have permission to manage this network. * *

Network owners will also be listed as administrators. * *

For NetworkCapability instances being sent from the System Server, this value MUST be * empty unless the destination is 1) the System Server, or 2) Telephony. In either case, the * receiving entity must have the ACCESS_FINE_LOCATION permission and target R+. * *

When received from an app in a NetworkRequest this is always cleared out by the system * server. This field is never used for matching NetworkRequests to NetworkAgents.

variables.name: LINK_BANDWIDTH_UNSPECIFIED
variables.comment:
* Value indicating that link bandwidth is unspecified.
     * @hide

variables.name: mLinkUpBandwidthKbps
variables.comment:
* Passive link bandwidth.  This is a rough guide of the expected peak bandwidth
     * for the first hop on the given transport.  It is not measured, but may take into account
     * link parameters (Radio technology, allocated channels, etc).

variables.name: SIGNAL_STRENGTH_UNSPECIFIED
variables.comment:
* Magic value that indicates no signal strength provided. A request specifying this value is
     * always satisfied.

variables.name: mSignalStrength
variables.comment:
* Signal strength. This is a signed integer, and higher values indicate better signal.
     * The exact units are bearer-dependent. For example, Wi-Fi uses RSSI.

variables.name: mUids
variables.comment:
* List of UIDs this network applies to. No restriction if null. *

* For networks, mUids represent the list of network this applies to, and null means this * network applies to all UIDs. * For requests, mUids is the list of UIDs this network MUST apply to to match ; ALL UIDs * must be included in a network so that they match. As an exception to the general rule, * a null mUids field for requests mean "no requirements" rather than what the general rule * would suggest ("must apply to all UIDs") : this is because this has shown to be what users * of this API expect in practice. A network that must match all UIDs can still be * expressed with a set ranging the entire set of possible UIDs. *

* mUids is typically (and at this time, only) used by VPN. This network is only available to * the UIDs in this list, and it is their default network. Apps in this list that wish to * bypass the VPN can do so iff the VPN app allows them to or if they are privileged. If this * member is null, then the network is not restricted by app UID. If it's an empty list, then * it means nobody can use it. * As a special exception, the app managing this network (as identified by its UID stored in * mOwnerUid) can always see this network. This is embodied by a special check in * satisfiedByUids. That still does not mean the network necessarily applies * to the app that manages it as determined by #appliesToUid. *

* Please note that in principle a single app can be associated with multiple UIDs because * each app will have a different UID when it's run as a different (macro-)user. A single * macro user can only have a single active VPN app at any given time however. *

* Also please be aware this class does not try to enforce any normalization on this. Callers * can only alter the UIDs by setting them wholesale : this class does not provide any utility * to add or remove individual UIDs or ranges. If callers have any normalization needs on * their own (like requiring sortedness or no overlap) they need to enforce it * themselves. Some of the internal methods also assume this is normalized as in no adjacent * or overlapping ranges are present. * * @hide

variables.name: mSSID
variables.comment:
* The SSID of the network, or null if not applicable or unknown. *

* This is filled in by wifi code. * @hide

methods.name: public int getOwnerUid()
methods.comment:
* Retrieves the UID of the app that owns this network. * *

For user privacy reasons, this field will only be populated if the following conditions * are met: * *

The caller is the network owner, AND one of the following sets of requirements is met: * *

    *
  1. The described Network is a VPN *
* *

OR: * *

    *
  1. The calling app is the network owner *
  2. The calling app has the ACCESS_FINE_LOCATION permission granted *
  3. The user's location toggle is on *
* * Instances of NetworkCapabilities sent to apps without the appropriate permissions will have * this field cleared out.

methods.name: public NetworkCapabilities setAdministratorUids(@NonNull final int[] administratorUids)
methods.comment:
* Sets the int[] of UIDs that are administrators of this network. * *

UIDs included in administratorUids gain administrator privileges over this Network. * Examples of UIDs that should be included in administratorUids are: * *

    *
  • Carrier apps with privileges for the relevant subscription *
  • Active VPN apps *
  • Other application groups with a particular Network-related role *
* *

In general, user-supplied networks (such as WiFi networks) do not have an administrator. * *

An app is granted owner privileges over Networks that it supplies. The owner UID MUST * always be included in administratorUids. * *

The administrator UIDs are set by network agents. * * @param administratorUids the UIDs to be set as administrators of this Network. * @throws IllegalArgumentException if duplicate UIDs are contained in administratorUids * @see #mAdministratorUids * @hide

methods.name: public int[] getAdministratorUids()
methods.comment:
* Retrieves the UIDs that are administrators of this Network. * *

This is only populated in NetworkCapabilities objects that come from network agents for * networks that are managed by specific apps on the system, such as carrier privileged apps or * wifi suggestion apps. This will include the network owner. * * @return the int[] of UIDs that are administrators of this Network * @see #mAdministratorUids * @hide

methods.name: public boolean equalsAdministratorUids(@NonNull final NetworkCapabilities nc)
methods.comment:
* Tests if the set of administrator UIDs of this network is the same as that of the passed one. * *

The administrator UIDs must be in sorted order. * *

nc is assumed non-null. Else, NPE. * * @hide

methods.name: private void combineAdministratorUids(@NonNull final NetworkCapabilities nc)
methods.comment:
* Combine the administrator UIDs of the capabilities. * *

This is only legal if either of the administrators lists are empty, or if they are equal. * Combining administrator UIDs is only possible for combining non-overlapping sets of UIDs. * *

If both administrator lists are non-empty but not equal, they conflict with each other. In * this case, it would not make sense to add them together.

* Tests if the set of UIDs that this network applies to is the same as the passed network. *

* This test only checks whether equal range objects are in both sets. It will * return false if the ranges are not exactly the same, even if the covered UIDs * are for an equivalent result. *

* Note that this method is not very optimized, which is fine as long as it's not used very * often. *

* nc is assumed nonnull. * * @hide

methods.name: public boolean satisfiedByUids(@NonNull NetworkCapabilities nc)
methods.comment:
* Test whether the passed NetworkCapabilities satisfies the UIDs this capabilities require. * * This method is called on the NetworkCapabilities embedded in a request with the * capabilities of an available network. It checks whether all the UIDs from this listen * (representing the UIDs that must have access to the network) are satisfied by the UIDs * in the passed nc (representing the UIDs that this network is available to). *

* As a special exception, the UID that created the passed network (as represented by its * mOwnerUid field) always satisfies a NetworkRequest requiring it (of LISTEN * or REQUEST types alike), even if the network does not apply to it. That is so a VPN app * can see its own network when it listens for it. *

* nc is assumed nonnull. Else, NPE. * @see #appliesToUid * @hide

methods.name: public boolean appliesToUidRange(@Nullable UidRange requiredRange)
methods.comment:

     * this method may return false even though all required UIDs are covered because no
     * single range contained them all.
     * @hide

methods.comment:
